<br>
I'm more posting in response to some of the discussion regarding 'elders' (which I assume to be what PC calls their officers) and guilds in general.<br>
<br>
I think that everyone realizes that as soon as a guild grows beyond a handful of people, the leader/officers start having to deal with a ton of issues, internal and external. what to kill, handling loot, guild relations, etc.  It's tough, can be very stressful, and is very timeconsuming.<br>
<br>
However, if you're expecting first shot at loot because that, you are out of line, IMHO.  That's blatant abuse of power.<br>
<br>
If your officers are at every event and the rest of teh guild is full of slackers, the officers would end up better geared ANYWAY, even if you go by /random, simply because of probability.. Ditto if you go by points.  There is no justification for intentionally gearing all your officers ahead of the rest of the guild roster.<br>
<br>
As someone else mentioned, if you really are paranoid about losing loot to random_member_01 who only shows up at certain raids...well, he's not a contributing member of the guild then is he?<br>
<br>
As Aamrie mentioned, everyone likes to get an upgrade every now and then.  Try to make sure whatever system you has spreads the wealth.  Even if there's no abuse of anything, if one person gets loot all the time, it breeds resentment and suspicion.<br>
<br>
Fully gearing up just one person leaves you exposed to other risks as well.  If you've given all good warrior loot to just 1 tank (for example) you're up the proverbial estuary without a means of locomotion if that person quits/has a broken computer/is on vacation/oversleeps, and 30+ other people are left standing around.<br>
<br>
Well, enough rambling for now.<br>
<br>
Aganerral Pardus<br>
